wellman_daniel wrote:
&gt; I&#39;ve got the need to test some legacy code which uses some hard-coded 
&gt; references to other concrete objects, or uses a service 
&gt; locator/factory to obtain other business objects.  I&#39;m reading J. B. 
&gt; Rainsberger&#39;s excellent &quot;JUnit Recipes&quot; book and this led me to check 
&gt; out mock objects.
 &gt;
&gt; 3. Does jMock with CGLib provide the functionality to intercept calls 
&gt; to concrete objects instantiated by the object under test? (As 
&gt; virtualmock appears to do)

Not directly. jMock is intended to help drive the design of your code, 
testing existing code is an added bonus if it works.

One thing you might consider is adding helper methods for object 
creation within the class, for example:

class Thing {
    void doIt(Blob aBlob) {
       aBlob.passThrough(new OtherThing());
    }
}

changes to:

class Thing {
    void doIt(Blob aBlob) {
       aBlob.passThrough(makeOtherThing());
    }
    OtherThing makeOtherThing() {
       return new OtherThing():
    }
}

You can then override makeOtherThing() in your test to introduce a mock.

This is not a pretty solution, but it&#39;s a workable interim step until a 
better structure becomes clearer.

S.
